narratives.question_text: What knowledge, skills, and insights did you develop by taking this course?
comments: This was an amazing first year math course at Yale. I learned various theorems, formulas, techniques, and applications of calculus.
The intersection between differentiation and Integration. Everything intro calculus.
Trig, integration, derivatives, and many other calculus principles.
I am so much more comfortable with Calculus!
Analytical reasoning, team work
I learned calculus.
I learned a lot of necessary calculus skills.

narratives.question_text: What are the strengths and weaknesses of this course and how could it be improved?
comments: I enjoyed the way this course was taught in class and greatly utilized office hours of Professor Hong to complete the problem sets.
It was a really well structured class and the topics followed each other in a logical order and the concepts build on each other.
The class work and office hours are both very helpful.

Strengths: extremely good professor and TAs

Weaknesses: some TAs were slightly disengaged from Office Hours
It was very well-taught and thorough.

Strengths - you learn a lot and have a lot of opportunities for office hours and improvement.
Weaknesses - covers a lot of material in a very short amount of time, can feel rushed

narratives.question_text: Would you recommend this course to another student? Please explain.
comments: Yes if you have the time to dedicate to it.
Yes, I would. While it is challenging, it is extremely rewarding and surprisingly fun.
Yes 110/111 will give a great calculus foundation and prepare you for higher level math classes if you need to take more
This course gives a comprehensive overview of calculus and precalculus principles.
Of course! Provides everyone with an outstanding Calculus foundation.
Yes. I really enjoyed going to the lectures because of how structured the lessons are and how easy the professor made me understand the concepts.
Yes, it is accessible even to students that have no background in calculus.
